Chi-squared: 159784.981 df(76), p.value < 0.001 
Nr obs: 87,535
  • The most statistically significant explanatory variables are ctrua, clua, impua and mobile_os. This is because the p values of these variables as you can see above are well below 0.05 which is our our cutoff for Type-1 error tolerance. If the p-value is above 0.05, there is a high chance that the explanatory variable will not have any effect on the response variable.
  • Odds is ratio of a probability of click to the probability of not clicking.
  • The odds ratios help us to understand the effect of these explanatory variables. The effects here are multiplicative. clua has an odds ratio of 1.295. This means that as clua increases by one unit, the odds of a click increases by 29.5%. impua on the other hand has an odds ratio of 0.979. This means that when impua increases by one unit, the odds of a click decreases by 2.129%. The odds ratio of ctrua is 1.022 which means that as ctrua increases by one unit, the odds of a click increases by 2.16%.
  • The intercept accounts for the effects of the android mobile os. IOS has an odds ratio of 0.450. This means that when the mobile OS is IOS, the odds of clicking decreases by 55% compared to an android. Other OS have an odds ratio of 0.719. This means that when the mobile OS is another one, the odds of clicking decreases by 28.09% compared to an android.
  • The pseudo R-squared talks about the fit of the model as a whole. It accounts for how much of the residual error is explained by the regression model. It has a value of 0.109 in this case, which is satisfactory. We could get a better fit if the number of observations in our training set was higher.The chi-squared p value of below 0.05 also indicates that all the explanatory variables have a significant effect on the response variable.

Discuss the implications of this (very) high level of collinearity and also different approaches to deal with it. What are the implications for the model and the interpretation of the estimated (standardized) coefficients? As part of your answer, discuss the change in the estimated (standardized) odd-ratio for imppat when you remove clpat from the model.

  • The VIF value for clpat and imppat are very high. This means that these variables can be regressed using the other variables and estimated to a large extent. This can skew our results and give us a wrong estimate. Multi-colinearity can be solved by removing one of the correlated variables from the model as the effects of these variables can be accounted for by just one of them.

dec_df_logit['cum number of impressions'] = dec_df_logit['number of impressions'].cumsum()

c. Discuss the similarities and differences between the two confusion matrices. Which model is best, based on the confusion matrix? Provide support for your conclusions. 4

  • Both models have a significantly low number negatives. This is a good sign as having a large number of false negatives can be costly for the company as it represents a large opportunity cost.
  • The second model however, does not do a good job of making predictions of the negative cases compared to the first model. The number of true negatives is much lower for the second model compared to the first. This is also reflected in the accuracy scores of the two models. This is a bad sign as a large number of false positives can mean a lot of wasted resources.
  • Hence model 1 is easily the better model of the two. It dies a good job of classifying both the positive and negative cases.

def perf_calc(df, mod, breakeven, which_model):
    
    df['click_logit'] = mod.predict(df)
    df['target_logit'] = df['click_logit'] > breakeven
    
    n_impressions = df['target_logit'].sum()
    tot_cost_impressions = n_impressions*cost_per_impression

    profit_nt = (profit*df.loc[df['target_logit'],'click_logit']).sum() 
    ROME = profit_nt/tot_cost_impressions

    print(f'The expected profit for {which_model} is ${round(profit_nt,2)} and the return on marketing expenditure is {round(ROME*100,2)}%')

    return (profit_nt,ROME)

def perf_calc_20M(df, mod, breakeven, which_model):
    
    df['click_logit'] = mod.predict(df)
    df['target_logit'] = df['click_logit'] > breakeven
    
    perc = df['target_logit'].mean()

    res_rate = df.loc[df['target_logit'],'click_logit'].mean()

    print(f'The expected profit for the 20 million impressions for {which_model} is ${round(profit_nt,2)} and the return on marketing expenditure is {round(ROME*100,2)}%')

    return (profit_nt,ROME)

def gains(df, mod, breakeven):
    
    df['click_logit'] = mod.predict(df)
    
    df['dec_logit'] = rsm.xtile(df['click_logit'],10, rev=True)
    df['click_yes'] = df['click_logit'] > breakeven
    
    dec_df_logit = df.groupby('dec_logit')['click_yes'].agg(['count','sum','mean']).reset_index()
    dec_df_logit.columns = ['dec_logit','number of impressions','number of clicks','click-through rate']
    
    dec_df_logit['cum number of clicks'] = dec_df_logit['number of clicks'].cumsum()
    
    tot_clicks = sum(dec_df_logit['number of clicks'])
    tot_impressions = sum(dec_df_logit['number of impressions'])
    
    dec_df_logit['cum number of impressions'] = dec_df_logit['number of impressions'].cumsum()
    dec_df_logit['cum prop of impressions'] = dec_df_logit['cum number of impressions']/tot_impressions

    dec_df_logit['gains'] = dec_df_logit['number of clicks']/tot_clicks
    dec_df_logit['cum gains'] = dec_df_logit['cum number of clicks']/tot_clicks
    
    return dec_df_logit
